{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Finally, MOND (Figure 2c) was proposed by DPG [86] and used in NSSG [53] as well.",
    "It aims at maximizing angles in the graph topology (cf.",
    "Definition 5), guiding the selection process via the angle threshold 𝜃 (e.g., 𝜃 = 60 •).",
    "MOND prunes the candidate neighbors of a node to favor edges pointing in different directions (𝑋 2 is pruned since ∠𝑋 1 𝑋 𝑞 𝑋 2 < 60 •, while 𝑋 𝑞 connects with 𝑋 3 since ∠𝑋 1 𝑋 𝑞 𝑋 3 > 60 • and with 𝑋 4 since ∠𝑋 1 𝑋 𝑞 𝑋 4 < 60 • and ∠𝑋 3 𝑋 𝑞 𝑋 4 < 60 •).",
    "Note that any nodes pruned by RRND and MOND will eventually be pruned by RND, but not vice versa."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Finally, MOND (Figure 2c) was proposed by DPG [86] and used in NSSG [53] as well."
  ]
}